{
  "title": "System Rationality and World Rationality",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8e9ce644ce8d638f",
      "text": "If you want to describe systems as rational in a critical, discriminatory sense, then it is not enough to refer to the existence or preservation of the existence. Existence can only simply be negated. That is not enough for rationality - neither as negation nor as negation of negation, as persistence, preservation, reproduction. Just as in the case of action it is not the mere occurrence or non-occurrence, but only the relational reconstruction of this contingency that makes rationality possible, a system can only gain rationality or be analyzed for its rationality if and to the extent that it is made contingent in its relational structure. This is achieved by the concept of complexity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5d5d7dbc02eea7fc",
      "text": "In this respect, the analyses of the concept of complexity with which we began our investigations were a preliminary study of the concept of rationality as applied to systems. As we recall, we had used the concept of complexity to describe the relationship between the purely quantitatively possible and the structurally seligized relations between items. According to this, complexity itself is a relation that relates size and structure to each other (or, to put it more precisely: that relates the relations that are possible in terms of size to those that are possible in terms of structure). If we imagine size and structure as variables, we are also dealing here with a relation that does not link any a priori fixed points of reference, but rather contingencies. The applicable rules of non-randomness must be sought in another relationship, namely in the relationship between system and environment."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f0b43a029ae5f26",
      "text": "Against the background of this general model (which has roughly the same significance for systems as the relation between means and ends in the theory of action), it can be seen that it only makes sense to speak of system rationality on the condition that the environment does not determine the system. If the relation between system and environment inevitably revealed which relations are actualized in the system, the reality of the system would be rational; the concept of rationality would lose its discriminating function, it would merge with the concept of existence and could be omitted."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "551ab4588b87a5e0",
      "text": "If, on the other hand, the relationship between the system and the environment itself is understood as contingent on both sides, a concept of rationality can be formulated that places certain demands on this relationship and, depending on this, on the system. Not all states that the relation can assume can then be considered rational. Such a concept of rationality must in any case be connectable to the problem of meaning-constituting negativity outlined above in section 1 of this chapter, and it must also utilize the insight gained in section 2 that contingency (and thus also negatability) can be expanded and reduced by means of relation and the relationization of relations. Everything else depends on how one understands contingency in system/environment relations."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0bf092f2a00a133f",
      "text": "Similar to the case of action rationality and for the same formal reasons, there are two models for this. Their distinction depends on whether the distinction between dependent and independent variables is assumed to be fixed or self-variable. As shown above, action can either pursue maximization or minimization strategies (exploitation or economy strategies) or optimization strategies. In the former case, the achievement of the purpose is maximized or the expenditure of resources is minimized, i.e. one side of the relation is fixed and the other is set up accordingly; in the latter case, the relation itself is varied in the direction of an optimum in comparison to other possibilities of the relation - which typically yields neither a minimum expenditure nor a maximum return. This alternative can be applied mutatis mutandis to the relation between system and environment. We call the two forms of rationality that result from this system rationality and world rationality."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "39a7c5fdb9ecc752",
      "text": "Of course, system rationality does not mean maximum exploitation of the environment. Nor is world rationality an optimal balancing of the relationships between system and environment. This kind of analogy would simply transfer the concept of action rationality to systems as actors and thus skip over the difference between action and system. In terms of systems theory, the relationship between system and environment must rather be understood as a relationship between complexes, as a complexity gradient. The rationality problem here does not lie, otherwise one would get by with the forms of action rationality, in bringing about estimated effects, but in the relation of intrinsically relational complexity relationships. The general rule also applies here: that relations have less contingency than the items they relate to each other."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "407cb2278428e45d",
      "text": "We can only speak of system rationality if the complexity of the environment is taken for granted and the system attempts to react to it with growth and/or structuring services. System rationality is adequate or environmentally appropriate intrinsic complexity. As complexity, it is structural self-limitation, since the system must react to an increase in size through structural selectivity. The concept of complexity also explains why enforced selectivity generates freedom with the opportunity to find more rational solutions to the complexity gap between the environment and the system. For the system, those solutions are more rational that allow for greater intrinsic complexity and can control its subsequent problems. At the operational level of action, high intrinsic complexity allows both interventions in the environment and selective changes to the system's own states, both at the level of items and relations and at the level of structures. The fixed point lies in the precondition of environmental complexity and the strategy in adapting to it. The higher intrinsic complexity conveys adaptive superiority in the form of a larger reservoir of relational possibilities that can be selectively decided upon. This is presumably what Parsons means by the term \"[[Adaptive Upgrading]]\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aef788551285ae38",
      "text": "Increasing intrinsic complexity is not rational because it increases the chances of survival; it is neither a requirement for survival nor a guarantee of survival. There are very less complex systems that have existed since time immemorial and, conversely, highly complex systems that have long since disappeared because their complexity disproportionately increased their dependence on the environment. But of course, in evolutionary terms, the ability to survive or reproduce is a prerequisite for the development of highly complex systems. Stability is one of the necessary evolutionary mechanisms which, together with others, makes it possible to build very complex systems. Rationality, on the other hand, is the term for the utilization of the evolutionary potential for negation in ways that must be compatible with stability if they are to be possible. From a theoretical point of view, this choice of term is therefore not determined by a preference for the preservation of everything that has come into being, but is ultimately controlled by the concept of world rationality, which is tailored to meaning and negation."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b7ab75d00e9e88b8",
      "text": "Even a theory of system preservation or system rationalization does not use the environmental term simply ecologically (in the sense of an objective totality of circumstances), but system-relatively. We use the concept of form to denote this system relativity. Forms are relations that are combined from the point of view of relevance for another system and that stand out against the background of other possibilities, selections, so to speak, from the possible selections of the environment or reductions of environmental complexity. The complexity of the environment appears to a system as a totality of forms that have special significance for the reference system. System rationality is oriented towards and proves itself in dealing with forms that appear contingent. However, form analysis, i.e. the analysis of forms as forms, leads to a different type of rationality, which we call world rationality."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dfbea0d80b5ded0a",
      "text": "Analysis of form is not already accomplished (but at best prepared) when forms are typified as general names and reduced to their formal idea, however \"profoundly\" these ideas may be formulated. Form as form can only be analytically disposed of when the system relativity of every environment becomes conscious. This requires a reconstruction of the contingency in the relation between system and environment. The relation itself is set contingent, namely as dependent on the choice of a system reference. As system-relatively reduced complexity brought to forms, the environment is always the environment of a system; it is therefore only self-referentially determinable for the system whose environment it is. One of the relations, the system, determines the other by determining the relation in which it stands to the other. Only in this way does the environment appear to the system as formed complexity. In the version now under discussion, the contingency of the system/environment relation is determined by the self-referentiality of its determinations. Its contingency is totalized in such a way that the reduction of complexity in the system and the environment are mutually dependent on each other; in other words, that the condensations of form in the environment are themselves conditioned by the way in which the system orders its own complexity. On the part of the systems, this presupposes a concept of their own identity, i.e. the ability to thematize themselves."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "011b1730e1fedbae",
      "text": "According to this, world rationality can only refer to the problem of how systems organize their environmental relations, provided that system complexity and formed environmental complexity are contingent and variable states. Criteria of world rationality would then in turn have to be criteria for the relation of relations, namely criteria for the relation of complexity relations (not simply: input/output relations!) between system and environment. Criteria for this, and this is the specific, distinguishing problem of world rationality, can no longer be established in non-negotiabilities - neither in a formal mathesis universalis nor in a system reference called subject, to which one (who?) could ascribe the hermeneutical primacy, so to speak. Any attempt of this kind would contradict the premises that meaning is constituted by negation and the world by systems-in-the-world and that self-referential structures and processes also occur outside science; it would therefore not be accommodated in a theory of the type sought here."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8a5c5428db28248b",
      "text": "Nevertheless, a concept of rationality, if it is to have any meaning of its own, must also discriminate with regard to the only self-referentially determinable double contingency of system/environment relations. In this case, it discriminates against only historical determinations. In self-referentially experienced, i.e. logically open and inconclusive relations, chance, the historical fact, initially becomes the determining factor. A society that thematizes itself self-referentially simultaneously experiences itself as historically conditioned. It understands itself as a phase of a process that has always already begun and has therefore already established irreversibilities and limited contingencies. Not logically, but factually, this excludes the actualization of every possibility. Society has to place itself in an environment that already existed before it and was established by earlier evolution. Its own historicity consists in the fact that its ability to combine experience and action socially and to relate them to the environment has been built up in evolutionary sequences that can neither be repeated nor restarted. At best, the environment and the system can be changed. This makes it understandable that modern society, with increased self-referential reflection, initially tends to experience contingency as historical facticity and, in contrast to this, the need for change and to understand itself as a world-historical process."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "200b6f5f69da46f0",
      "text": "A concept of rationality that opposes this syndrome is not available. The universal positive evaluation of critique seems to provide a kind of substitute satisfaction. Criticism is only directed against systemic history and for this very reason does not free us from historical ties. Precisely the most potent critics of bourgeois society therefore remain bourgeois theorists. Their critique does not achieve the reorientation of the social system from history to environment that we discussed above; rather, it merely expresses the syndrome of reflection, historicity and the intention to change."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7cfc807ef9425be3",
      "text": "World rationality is something other than this criticism-generating and reproducing syndrome. It should be able to emerge from historical conditions and intentions for change in environments and systems. For this, a concept and a procedure would have to be found with which to relate self-referential relations of the characterized type. At the same time, this desideratum goes beyond the form of system-theoretical analysis used so far, which presupposed the preliminary decision on the choice of a system reference as a decision on the standpoint of totalizing reflection. Even recourse to the world perspective of the most comprehensive social system, society, would not suffice if this very perspective were to be questioned with regard to rationality. Totalizing perspectives of this kind would have to be related for their part, and, since they are already self-revealing and all-revealing world perspectives, they would have to be related to each other. This requires models of thought that can take into account a majority of system references."
    },
