      "type": "edit",
      "id": "b7ab75d00e9e88b8",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b7ab75d00e9e88b8",
        "text": "Even a theory of system preservation or system rationalization does not use the environmental term simply ecologically (in the sense of an objective totality of circumstances), but system-relatively. We use the concept of form to denote this system relativity. Forms are relations that are combined from the point of view of relevance for another system and that stand out against the background of other possibilities, selections, so to speak, from the possible selections of the environment or reductions of environmental complexity. The complexity of the environment appears to a system as a totality of forms that have special significance for the reference system. System rationality is oriented towards and proves itself in dealing with forms that appear contingent. However, form analysis, i.e. the analysis of forms as forms, leads to a different type of rationality, which we call world rationality."
      },
      "date": 1704319628017
