      "type": "edit",
      "id": "dfbea0d80b5ded0a",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "dfbea0d80b5ded0a",
        "text": "Analysis of form is not already accomplished (but at best prepared) when forms are typified as general names and reduced to their formal idea, however \"profoundly\" these ideas may be formulated. Form as form can only be analytically disposed of when the system relativity of every environment becomes conscious. This requires a reconstruction of the contingency in the relation between system and environment. The relation itself is set contingent, namely as dependent on the choice of a system reference. As system-relatively reduced complexity brought to forms, the environment is always the environment of a system; it is therefore only self-referentially determinable for the system whose environment it is. One of the relations, the system, determines the other by determining the relation in which it stands to the other. Only in this way does the environment appear to the system as formed complexity. In the version now under discussion, the contingency of the system/environment relation is determined by the self-referentiality of its determinations. Its contingency is totalized in such a way that the reduction of complexity in the system and the environment are mutually dependent on each other; in other words, that the condensations of form in the environment are themselves conditioned by the way in which the system orders its own complexity. On the part of the systems, this presupposes a concept of their own identity, i.e. the ability to thematize themselves."
      },
      "date": 1704319674373
